    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.02915.001.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <date when="1890-10-03">October 3rd 1890.</date>
                    <name type="place">The North American Review.</name>
                    <name type="place">3 East Fourteenth Street, New York.<ptr target="loc.02915_n1"
                        /></name>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Dear Sir:&#8212;</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>Can you write a brief article for the <hi rend="underline">North American Review</hi>
                on Recent Aspects of American Literature as you have observed them? It need not be
                more than 4000 words in length&#8212;about ten pages of the <hi rend="underline"
                    >Review</hi>&#8212;and in return for it we should be glad to place at your
                disposal the sum of Two hundred dollars. Or possibly there is some other subject on
                which</p>

            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.02915.002.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc.02915.003.jpg" type="recto"/>

            <p>you would be more willing to write. In that case we trust you will allows us an
                opportunity to consider it.<ptr target="loc.02915_n2"/></p>

            <closer>
                <salute>I am, dear Sir,</salute>
                <salute>Faithfully Yours,</salute>
                <signed>William H. Rideing,</signed>
                <signed>assistant editor of the <hi rend="underline">Review.</hi></signed>
            </closer>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002v" facs="loc.02915.004.jpg" type="verso"/>
        </body>
